2026-04-21 01:26:36 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['main load lamp (bulb) in load module'] hypothesis_explanation='The system has correct power: the power‑supply green LED is on, and the polarity and cabling have been exhaustively swapped without ever turning on the main lamp or the red inverted‑cables LED. The internal indicator lamp in the load module, which is wired directly in parallel with the main lamp and behind the same series diode, does light. That means:\n\n- 12 V is reaching the load module with correct polarity (otherwise the diode would block current and neither lamp would light).\n- The series path through the control module and switch is intact whenever the indicator lamp is lit.\n- Therefore, any fault upstream (power supply, control switch, wiring, series diode) is ruled out, because those elements are shared by both bulbs.\n\nThe only component that can prevent the main lamp from lighting while allowing the parallel indicator lamp to light is the main lamp itself (open filament or internal failure). Hence the root cause is a failed/open main load lamp in the load module.'
